# Largest Element in an Array

## Problem
Given an array `arr`, find the largest element in the array.

Example:

Input:
```
arr = [3,7,2,9,5]
```

Output:
```
9
```

---

# Approach 1: Brute Force (Sorting)

### Idea
Sort the array and return the last element.

### Code

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int largestElement(vector<int>& arr) {
    int n = arr.size();
    sort(arr.begin(), arr.end());
    return arr[n-1];
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr = {3,7,2,9,5};
    cout << largestElement(arr);
}
```

### Complexity
Time Complexity: `O(n log n)`  
Space Complexity: `O(1)`

---

# Approach 2: Better Approach (Linear Scan)

### Idea
Traverse the array and keep updating the largest element.

### Code

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int largestElement(vector<int>& arr) {
    int largest = arr[0];

    for(int i = 1; i < arr.size(); i++) {
        if(arr[i] > largest) {
            largest = arr[i];
        }
    }

    return largest;
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr = {3,7,2,9,5};
    cout << largestElement(arr);
}
```

### Complexity
Time Complexity: `O(n)`  
Space Complexity: `O(1)`

---

# Approach 3: Optimal Approach (Using STL)

### Idea
Use the C++ STL function `max_element()`.

### Code

```cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int largestElement(vector<int>& arr) {
    return *max_element(arr.begin(), arr.end());
}

int main() {
    vector<int> arr = {3,7,2,9,5};
    cout << largestElement(arr);
}
```

### Complexity
Time Complexity: `O(n)`  
Space Complexity: `O(1)`
